<font color="#FF0000">MY THOUGTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Sep  2 12:48:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all,<br>
Some very emotional responses!  The legacy of Vietnam is a strong one.  My emotional realization came when I visited the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington DC.  I began looking up names of casualties my family had known.  The more I looked up, the more artifacts I saw, the more it got to me.  There I was a person a generation removed, somehow connected to people who died before I was born.  What hit me was how some of these men were my age, back during the war, and now there gone-they stopped living then.  What could they have been?  Who might they have become?<br><br>
It just increased my respect of the warrior of that war.  To have to have lived through that must have been incredible.  War in all forms is a hell, a test of wills and survival.  I agree there are times to fight.  I would fight like hell to defend the freedoms of this country, but there are times not to fight.  Hindsight is 20/20 and I'm in no position to declare the war wrong or right.  The line of hawk or dove is idiotic to me.  I'm not a dove, because I believe in standing up for ones self, but I'm not a true hawk, because I can't see fighting a war that is not in defense of freedoms.<br><br>
To Tom,<br>
I may have disagreed with you before, but perhaps I didn't make myself clear.  I hate war, especially the Vietnam war.  I'm not a person who will insult the Vietnamese people with cheap vulgarity such as &quot;gook&quot; or &quot;slope&quot;.  War is a dehumaizer, a time and place where so-called modern, socially conscious society drops down to the lowest form of existence-SURVIVAL.  To place people in that position, is horrible.  Sometimes it has to be done, but for the most part it doesn't have to be done.  Vietnam did more to churn and twist this country than most other events this century.  Don't kid yourself, I hate a useless war.  I have a younger brother and if another war like Vietnam broke out, I do what I had to do to keep him and others out, carry signs etc.  That may sound horrible, but I've seen too much of the Vietnam aftermath (not the war itself) to convince me otherwise.<br><br>
I may speak out for the Vietnam vet, but I'm not speaking out for the war.  I can separate the two, something some (notice I only said some) of the protestors couldn't do.  Vietnam vets have been dragged around enough already, they don't have to be condemned for it.  War is the dehumanizer!  No one gave the Vietnam vet a chance to ask Why, that can only be done today.  But will there ever be one answer.  There can be respect for service and the men wothout undue glory.  One has to be proud of the men and women that serve and in the process give something of themselves, they do something more than the average person.  I wish you would define your definition of Glory.  Is Glory pride?  I doubt many people take true pride in killing  (I don't).  My pride in the Vietnam soldier is in any man or woman who went and gave a little of themselves.  So may lives have been changed by Vietnam, so are we to tell the men who served, it was not worth it?  Are to tell the PTSD suffers-forget about it, it doesn't matter? There has to be some recognition, if not to just bring peace and piece of mind to a divided generation and a America whose wounds still bleed of Vietnam, not to mention a country of Vietnam whos till suffers.  Everything has to have meaning in life.  Thus, I can recognize the warrior (of both sides), even knowing what a warrior does.  What a combat soldier is, is just a manifestation of us, all of us, mankind, and what a human can do by nature.  Remember what the comic strip character POGO said, &quot;We have seen the enemy and he is us&quot;.<br><br>
Peace!!          
<p><code>-- posted  (Joe DeLeva) </code><p>


